How Ortega can cease to be the president of Nicaragua before 11 Jan 2021

Daniel Ortega has been in power since he won the elections in 2006. He managed to get a Supreme Court ruling allowing him to be re-elected. The authorities of the State are monopolized by his party (FSLN). One of them is the Supreme Electoral Council, whose system needs profound reforms to guarantee free, fair and transparent elections. So far, 9 months before the November elections, the government has shown no signs of willingness to guarantee the conditions that would allow the opposition to participate in elections; on the contrary, in the last six months the legislature has approved a series of laws that seek to limit the political participation of organizations and parties and to disqualify opposition candidates. In addition, there remains a constant siege against opposition leaders. Added to this is the lack of consensus and unity of the opposition groups. Ortega could agree to certain technical reforms, but without sufficiently leveling the ground for the opposition. Ortega's latest onslaught against the business sector, the only sector with which he has sat down to negotiate in the past and now seeks to weaken it, must be taken into account. However, taking into account that there is pressure from the international community (governments and multilateral organizations) for electoral reforms; that 70% of the population (Cid Gallup, January 2021) does not have a political party of preference and that the opposition still has a chance to reach an agreement, I give a 15% probability.

The economy is in deep recession, response to the Covid pandemic has been woeful but, Ortega holds control of all the key government institutions and is repressing any opposition, journalists or the media. Nicaragua has shown a resilience to ignore International pressure that gives a possible nervous rationale to increase the repression by passing laws claiming all opposition to be traitors and terrorists. Ortega‚Äôs Sandinista party gained a 79% majority in Congress allowing him total control over the army, police, rule by decree and to run for election indefinitely. In a country with a population of 6.6 million, 100,000 citizens and about 90 journalists have fled Nicaragua for surrounding countries and the opposition is divided. Therefore, only a coup is likely to remove him), so probably unlikely.
